Context

This data is from the M5 Accuracy Competition. These competitions have been running for around 40 years, and are used to compare forecasting methods and determine which ones tend to be best to improve the field as a whole. This particular dataset represents Walmart’s hierarchical unit sales for select stores, departments, and items. There are 3049 unique items, and when you account for for combinations with higher levels there’s a total of 42,840 time series in data.

EDA

There are 1941 days worth of data and 35 unique items in the subset of the dataset used for analysis. The data was restricted to a random sample of 10 items per department as this is meant to just be a demonstration of what is possible.

The number of unique items appears to be uniform across stores, but different by department. So if I need to subset the data to deal with memory, I should probably group by department when obtaining a sample of items to use. Each item id is represented in each store, so I’m not sure grouping by store will accomplish anything in particular.

trend_vs_seasonality_plot

The graphs are a bit difficult to read, so I am going to try grouping by week to see if that makes them a bit easier. There is moderately strong weekly seasonality and strong trend for a few of the departments, although the strength of the trend and seasonality seem to differ, so the data will likely benefit from using different models based on the time series.

Code
ts_plot_weekly <- 
    ts %>%
  as_tibble() %>% 
  mutate(ds=yearweek(ds),
         ds=as.Date(ds)) %>% 
  group_by(ds) %>% 
  summarize(sold=sum(sold)) %>% 
  as_tsibble(index=ds)%>% 
           plot_time_series(ds, sold,
                            # varname,
                            .facet_ncol = 3, 
                            .facet_scales = "free",
                            .y_lab="sold",
                            .title = str_c("Time Series Plot of items sold")
                            )

There seems to be some sort of consistent seasonality for the overall data, and some sort of trend (although it does change over time). However, given the scale of the remainder, trend and seasonality don’t account for all of the variation in contracts.

horizon <- 52

ts1 <- ts %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  group_by(ds, !!sym(level1)) %>% 
  summarize(sold=sum(sold)) %>% 
  mutate(sku=str_c(!!sym(level1))) %>%
  as_tsibble(index=ds,key=sku) %>% 
  fill_gaps(
    sold=0,
    .full=TRUE
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    sold=ifelse(is.na(sold),0,sold)
  )

Reconciling

  • Explanation
  • Code

The source code for the fable reconcilliation function has the final reconcilliation as:

```{r}
S <- matrix(0L, nrow = length(agg_data$agg),
            ncol = max(vec_c(!!!agg_data$agg)))
# !!! is usually used to evaluate a list of expressions.
# It seems to be similar to !!

    S[length(agg_data$agg)*(vec_c(!!!agg_data$agg)-1) +
        rep(seq_along(agg_data$agg), lengths(agg_data$agg))] <- 1L

    R <- t(S)%*%solve(W)
    P <- solve(R%*%S)%*%R
```

So step 1: S is a matrix of m x n with m being the number of levels of aggregation and everything is a 0 e.g. given the earlier example forecast, it should look like: $ [ ] $

Step 2: I’m pretty sure this is building the sum matrix. If you think of matrix S as having the names of the aggregation level and value along the left side and the value of the bottom level along the top (e.g.  [ ] ), then anywhere the top is included in the group on the left (e.g. y_AA is included in all ys, all y_As, and y_AA, but not in y_B) there should be a one, which would look like: [ ] Step 3: This is taking the transpose of S, and the inverse of W (which should be defined earlier based on what reconcilliation method you’re using), and then multiplying them.

Step 4: This is multiplying the results of step 3 by S, then taking the inverse, and then multiplying that by the results of step 3. This can also be broken down a bit more (which I’m doing for trouble shooting 1 purposes)

I’ve created the summing matrix earlier and checked that it looks right. For a little bit I thought maybe I was creating the summing matrix incorrectly (despite it working on my last project), but if you look at the paper MinT was written in 2, (half-paraphrased, half-quoted)

  • let \(y_t\) be an \(m\)-vector containing all observations at time \(t\) and \(b_t\) be and \(n\)-vector containing the observations at the most disaggregated level only (the “bottom” level)
  • This leads to the convenient general matrix representation : \(y_t = Sb_t\)
  • Where \(S\) is a “summing matrix” of order \(m\) x \(n\) (so total number of levels in hierarchy x number of most granular items in hierarchy) which aggregates the bottom level series to the series at aggregation levels above.
  • Each aggregation constraint is represented by a row in the summing matrix S pg 4-5

Additionally, the formula above omits the first multiplication by the summing matrix and multiplying it by the forecasts. As far as I can tell, this happens later in the function. The formula I use is from [paper] :

\(\tilde{y}_h=S(S'W_h^{-1}S)^{-1}S'W_h^{-1}\hat{y}_h\)

This is to define the bottom level for creating summing matrices

  • Explanation
  • Code

If we generate unbiased base forecasts \(\hat{y}_h\), then optimally reconciled forecasts are given by: \(\tilde{y}_h=S(S'W_h^{-1}S)^{-1}S'W_h^{-1}\hat{y}_h\)

Where S: the summing matrix, e.g. for forecast y with levels A,B,AA,AB,AC,BA,BB [ = ] \(\hat{y}_h\): is the unbiased base forecast \(W_h^-1\): is \(Var[(y_{T+h}−\tilde{y}_h)]\) is the variance-covariance matrix of the corresponding base forecast errors. - However, this has to be estimated in most real world scenarios - There are several ways to do this 1. Ordinary Least Squares Set \(W_h=k_hI\) for all h, where k_h > 0 - This is equivalent to \(\hat{β}=(X′X)^{−1}X′y\) with X=S and y=\(\hat{y\)} so \(\hat{β}=(S′S)^{−1}S′y\) 3 2. sample MinT \(W_h = k_h \hat{W}_1 , \forall h\) where \(k_h >0\), the unrestricted sample covariance estimator for h=1. This might not work well for m > T or the order of m = the order of T. (paper 9) 3. structural WLS \(W_h = k_h \lambda, \forall h,\) where \(k_h > 0\) and \(\lambda = diag(S1)\) and 1 is a unit column vector of dimension n. This assumes each bottom level forecast has a variance \(k_h\) and are uncorrelated between nodes. So the diagonal \(\lambda\) contains the number of forecast error variances contributing to an aggregation level. This only assumes equivarient forecast errors within a level, which is more realistic than OLS which assumes the forecast errors are equivarient across levels. It’s especially useful when forecast errors are not available.
4. Variance Scaling WLS \(W_h = k_h diag(\hat{W_1}), \forall h,\) where \(k_h >0\) and \(\hat{W}_1=\frac{1}{T}\sum^T_{t=1}\hat{e_t}(1)\hat{e_t}(1)'\) which is the unbiased sample estimator of the in-sample one-step-ahead base forecast errors (\(e_t\) are the residuals from back testing). 5. MinT shrink \(W_h=k_h\hat(W)^∗_{1,D}, \forall h\) where: \(k_h >0\) \(\hat(W)^∗_{1,D}=\lambda_D\hat(W)_{1,D}+(1-\lambda_D)\hat{W_1}\) is a shrinkage estimator with diagonal target \(\hat{W}_{1,D}\) is a diagonal matrix comprising the diagonal entries of \(\hat{W}_1\) \(\lambda_D\) is the shrinkage intensity parameter So, off-diagonal elements of \(\hat{W_1}\) are shrunk towards zero, and diagonal elements (variances) stay the same. Assuming variances are constant, \(\hat{\lambda}_D = \frac{\sum_{i=\=j} \hat{Var(\hat{r_{ij}})}}{\sum_{i=\=j} (\hat{r^2_{ij}})}\) where \(\hat{r_{ij}}\) is the \(ij\)th element of \(\hat{R_1}\), the 1-step-ahead sample correlation matrix to shrink it towards an identity matrix. (fpp3) -1 : inverse ’ : transpose

I’ve only implemented a few of these, I plan on adding the others later. The code comes from some combination of figuring out how to translate the math into R code and occasionally copying the code from the fable package (usually because their way is much cleaner than mine).

This breaks down the reconciliation step by step. I’ve got a section later that does it in one go, but this is helpful for trouble shooting and also for double checking the math -> code conversion.

For OLS the formula is a bit different (W gets omitted), but for all other reconcilliation methods the formula is: S %*% (matlib::Ginv((t(S) %*% solve(W) %*% S))) %*% t(S) %*% solve(W) %*% samplefcmat

Code

step3 <- step2 %*% S

forecastcheckgraph <- function(df,toplevelofinterest,
                               # bottomlevelofinterest,
                               toplevelname
                               # bottomlevelname
                               ){
  a <-   ggplotly(
     df %>% 
  filter(!!sym(toplevelname)==toplevelofinterest,
         # !!sym(bottomlevelname)==bottomlevelofinterest
         ) %>% 
  #mutate(ds=yearweek(str_c(year," Wk",week))) %>% 
    group_by(!!sym(toplevelname), ds, .model) %>% 
    mutate(sold=sum(sold)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=ds,y=sold, color=.model))+
  geom_line(aes(linetype=.model),size=1)+
  theme_minimal()
  
  #geom_line(aes(y=unitssold),color="black")
) %>% 
  plotly::layout(title = list(text = paste0(
    'Forecasts for ',toplevelofinterest, ' '#, bottomlevelofinterest
                                    # '<br>',
                                    # '<sup>',
                                    # 'Chosen Model:', chosenModel,
                                    # '</sup>'
    )))


b <-   
  ggplotly(df %>%
    filter(
      !!sym(toplevelname)==toplevelofinterest,
         # !!sym(bottomlevelname)==bottomlevelofinterest
         ) %>% 
       group_by(!!sym(toplevelname), ds, .model) %>% 
    mutate(sold=sum(sold)) %>% 
  ggplot( 
       aes(x = .model, 
           y = sold, 
           color = .model)) +
  geom_boxplot(size=1,
               outlier.shape = 1,
               outlier.color = "black",
               outlier.size  = 3) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.15,
              width=.2) +
    #geom_violin()+
  labs(x = "",
       y = "") +
  theme_minimal())
things <- list()
things$plota <- a
things$plotb <- b
return(things)
}

acc <- rbind((BackTestststdf %>% mutate(ds=as.Date(ds))),
             baseline_fc) %>% 
left_join(full_sku_historicals, by=c("sku","ds") ) %>% 
  mutate(forecast=ifelse(forecast<0,0,round(forecast)),
         .resid=sold-forecast
         ) %>% 
  group_by(sku,.model,scenario) %>% 
  mutate(RMSE=sqrt(mean(.resid^2, na.rm=TRUE)),
         MAE=mean(abs(.resid), na.rm=TRUE))

fullacc <- rbind((fullBackTestststdf %>% mutate(ds=as.Date(ds))),

model_compare <- function(df, fulldf = NULL) {
  
  
  a <- (
    df %>% 
  group_by(.model) %>% 
  
summarize(RMSE=median(RMSE, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%   
  ggplot( aes(fill=.model, y=RMSE, x=.model))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  labs(x="errors", title="Median RMSE by Model")
  )
  
  b <- (df %>% 
          group_by(sku) %>% 
          slice_min(n=1,RMSE) %>% 
          ggplot(aes(x=.model, fill=.model))+
          geom_bar()+
          labs(title="Models won using RMSE"))
  
  
  c <- (
    df %>% 
  group_by(.model) %>% 
  
summarize(MAE=median(MAE, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%   
  ggplot( aes(fill=.model, y=MAE, x=.model))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  labs(x="errors", title="Median MAE by Model")
  )
  
  d <- (df %>% 
          group_by(sku) %>% 
          slice_min(n=1,MAE) %>% 
          ggplot(aes(x=.model, fill=.model))+
          geom_bar()+
          labs(title="Models won using MAE"))
  if (!is.null(fulldf)){
    e <- (fulldf %>% 
  group_by(.model) %>% 
  
summarize(RMSE=median(RMSE, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%   
  ggplot( aes(fill=.model, y=RMSE, x=.model))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  labs(x="errors", title="Median RMSE by Model for all models")
  )
    f <- (fulldf %>% 
      group_by(.model) %>% 
  
summarize(MAE=median(MAE, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%   
  ggplot( aes(fill=.model, y=MAE, x=.model))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  labs(x="errors", title="Median MAE by Model for all Models")
  )
  }
  
  
  
  things <- list()

  things$models_median_RMSE <- a
  things$models_won_RMSE <- b
  things$models_median_MAE <- c
  things$models_won_MAE <- d
  if (!is.null(fulldf)){
    things$full_models_median_RMSE <- e
    things$full_models_median_MAE <- f
  }
  
  # print(things)
  return(things)
  
  }
